# Veda — AI-Powered PDF to Interactive Presentation Web App
# Cursor Rules File — paste this in project root as .cursorrules

## What This Project Is
Veda converts any uploaded PDF into an interactive narrated presentation with
karaoke-style word highlighting. The user uploads a PDF, the backend extracts
layout per page, a local LLM generates slide JSON (title, subtitle, summary,
highlights, narration), and Sarvam AI handles TTS + STT for word-level timestamps.
The mascot is Zoro — a cartoon elephant avatar (New_Zoro.png) to be animated via
HeyGen Talking Photo API.

---

## Project Structure

```
veda/
  server/
    tts_server.py         ← Main FastAPI backend (single file, 1083 lines)
    .env                  ← API keys (SARVAM_API_KEY, OPENAI_API_KEY)
    vendor/               ← pip-installed packages (edge-tts, fastapi, etc.)
    models/               ← Local GGUF model files (Qwen2.5)
    active_doc.pdf        ← Currently loaded PDF (written on upload)

  src/
    App.jsx               ← Root React component
    main.jsx              ← Vite entry point
    index.css
    components/
      AIAvatar.jsx        ← Animated avatar component (to be replaced by Zoro video)
      LeftPanel.jsx       ← PDF TOC sidebar
      RightPanel.jsx      ← Main presentation + karaoke (2100+ lines)
    context/
      PDFContext.jsx      ← useReducer + Context API for global state
    utils/
      pdfUtils.js         ← PDF.js utilities
      speechUtils.js      ← Speech/audio utilities
```

---

## Backend — tts_server.py (FastAPI, port 8765)

### API Endpoints
| Method | Path | What it does |
|--------|------|--------------|
| GET | /health | Health check |
| POST | /upload_pdf | Accepts raw PDF bytes, saves as active_doc.pdf, opens with PyMuPDF |
| GET | /page_layout?page=N | Returns { width, height, lines[], images[] } for page N |
| POST | /analyze | Runs local LLM on extracted text, returns slide JSON |
| POST | /tts | Sarvam TTS → returns { audio (base64 WAV), word_boundaries[] } |
| GET | /tts_stream | Streams audio (Sarvam or edge-tts fallback) |
| POST | /tts_boundaries | Returns only word_boundaries (no audio) |
| POST | /transcribe | OpenAI Whisper STT → returns { text, word_boundaries[] } |

### Key Classes & Functions
- `SarvamMemoryCache` — in-memory single-entry cache (text+lang+voice+rate as key)
- `LLMState` — singleton for llama-cpp Qwen model, lazy-loads on first /analyze call
- `PDFMetadataAnalyzer` — detects repeating headers/footers across pages to filter them
- `detect_speech_boundaries(wav_bytes)` — finds lead-in/lead-out silence in WAV
- `adjust_boundaries_to_silence(boundaries, wav_bytes)` — corrects STT timestamps for Sarvam's 150-570ms padding
- `generate_fallback_boundaries(text, duration)` — proportional timestamp fallback if STT fails
- `analyze_text_semantic(text, is_digest, language)` — calls Qwen LLM, parses JSON response with auto-repair
- `translate_strings_sarvam(texts, api_key)` — batch translates to Telugu via Sarvam Translate API

### LLM Config
- Default model: Qwen2.5-0.5B-Instruct (GGUF, Q4_K_M quantization)
- Model size controlled by env var `LOCAL_LLM_SIZE` (0.5B / 1.5B / 3B)
- Loaded via llama-cpp-python with n_ctx=2048, n_threads=min(8, cpu_count)
- Model paths checked: server/models/, C:/Users/eakes/.gemini/... (hardcoded, needs fixing for GPU server)
- JSON auto-repair built in (_extract_json) because small models produce malformed JSON

### Translation
- Currently uses Sarvam Translate API (batch mode with |#| delimiter)
- Only narration fields are translated, not titles/bullets
- Target: replace with IndicTrans2 (better contextual quality, free, runs on GPU server)

### Known Issues / Things to Watch
1. Model path has hardcoded `C:/Users/eakes/` paths — must be updated for GPU server deployment
2. LLMState loads model with n_gpu_layers=0 (CPU only) — needs `n_gpu_layers=-1` for GPU server
3. SarvamMemoryCache is single-entry only — second unique request evicts the first
4. /transcribe uses OpenAI Whisper API (costs money) — Sarvam STT used for karaoke instead
5. CORS is wide open (allow_origins=["*"]) — fine for demo, restrict before production

---

## Frontend — React 19 + Vite

### State Management
- Global state via useReducer + Context API in PDFContext.jsx
- No Redux, no Zustand

### Key Components
- `RightPanel.jsx` — 2100+ lines, handles slide rendering, karaoke highlighting, audio playback, language toggle
- `LeftPanel.jsx` — TOC sidebar, PDF upload trigger
- `AIAvatar.jsx` — currently a static animated SVG/CSS avatar (Veda robot), to be replaced by Zoro video

### PDF Processing Flow
1. User uploads PDF in LeftPanel
2. Frontend sends raw bytes to POST /upload_pdf
3. Frontend calls GET /page_layout?page=N for each page
4. For each page, frontend calls POST /analyze with extracted text
5. LLM returns slide JSON → rendered as slide card in RightPanel
6. On play: POST /tts → gets audio + word_boundaries → karaoke starts

---

## Karaoke Sync — How It Works
Sarvam TTS does NOT return word timestamps natively. Two-step pipeline:
1. POST to Sarvam TTS → get WAV audio
2. POST that audio to Sarvam STT → get word-level timestamps
3. detect_speech_boundaries() measures actual silence padding in WAV
4. adjust_boundaries_to_silence() rescales STT timestamps to match real audio
5. If STT returns chunked segments instead of words → fallback to proportional heuristic

---

## Environment Variables (.env)
```
SARVAM_API_KEY=your_key_here
OPENAI_API_KEY=your_key_here   # Optional, only for /transcribe endpoint
LOCAL_LLM_SIZE=0.5B            # Options: 0.5B, 1.5B, 3B
```

